This shouldn't be an issue for backwards compatibility. The `maxDistance`/`z` value is only internally used by the `PlaceHeldObject` function. `PlaceHeldObject` is onlyu called by `PutObject` which never exposed the  `maxDistance`/`z` to the python controller.

The original versions of `PutObject` were:

```       
        //Target what receptacle to put a held object via (x, y) screen coordinates
        public void PutObject(float x, float y, bool forceAction=false, bool placeStationary=true){
            PlaceHeldObject(x, y, forceAction, placeStationary);
        }

        //Target what receptacle to put a held object via objectId directly
        public void PutObject(string objectId, bool forceAction=false, bool placeStationary=true){
            PlaceHeldObject(objectId, forceAction, placeStationary);
        }
 ```
 
The new versions included in this update still don't expose or change the default values of `maxDistance`/`z` , but they do add new optional parameters of `randomSeed` and `putNearXY`

```        
        public void PutObject(float x, float y, bool forceAction=false, bool placeStationary=true, int 
        randomSeed=0, bool putNearXY=false){
            PlaceHeldObject(
                x: x, 
                y: y,
                forceAction: forceAction, 
                placeStationary: placeStationary,
                randomSeed: randomSeed,
                putNearXY: putNearXY);
        }

        public void PutObject(string objectId, bool forceAction=false, bool placeStationary=true, 
        int randomSeed=0){
            PlaceHeldObject(                
                objectId: objectId,
                forceAction: forceAction,
                placeStationary: placeStationary,
                randomSeed: randomSeed);
        }
```

