ChatGPT says:

-------

Yes, using placement new to reinitialize an object at the same memory location can be a good option in some cases. However, you need to be careful when using placement new with const fields.

If your OpSchema class has const fields, you cannot reassign their values directly. Instead, you need to use a constructor that initializes those fields during object construction. One way to achieve this is to use an initialization list in the constructor.

Here's an example that demonstrates how to use placement new to reinitialize an object of type OpSchema at the same memory location:

```c++
void resetOpSchema(OpSchema& self, const OpSchema& schema) {
    // Call destructor to destroy the existing object
    self.~OpSchema();

    // Use placement new to construct a new object at the same memory location
    new (&self) OpSchema(schema);
}
```

In this example, the resetOpSchema function takes a reference to an existing OpSchema object (self) and a reference to a const OpSchema object (schema). It first calls the destructor of OpSchema to destroy the existing object at the memory location pointed to by self.

Next, it uses placement new to construct a new OpSchema object at the same memory location. The new operator calls the constructor of OpSchema and passes schema as its argument. The constructor initializes all non-const fields of the OpSchema object, including any const fields that are initialized in the constructor's initialization list.

Note that this technique assumes that the existing object at the memory location pointed to by self was previously constructed using placement new. If the object was constructed using other means, you need to make sure that its memory allocation and alignment match the requirements of the OpSchema class.

